The decision sheet — picking the right access control. This is the whole module on one page: you read the scenario, and you pick the control.

Give analysts read access to gold tables — grant use-catalog, plus use-schema, plus select; all three. Block one table for a group despite a catalog-level grant — deny, because deny beats grant. Hide the P-A-N from analysts but show last-four to the fraud team — a column mask. Restrict compliance analysts to their region's rows — a row filter. Apply masks and filters to every P-I-I-tagged column across hundreds of tables — Unity Catalog A-B-A-C. Fine-grained control for a non-U-C client, or a very simple case — a dynamic view, the legacy option. Forensic audit, who read this table last Tuesday — system-dot-access-dot-audit. Track column-level read-write lineage — system-dot-access-dot-table-lineage, plus the Lineage tab. And production grants for a team — always to a group, not to individuals.

If you hold just three tells, you'll unlock most of these questions. One: whenever you see "read access," remember the trio — use-catalog, use-schema, and select — because the answer that omits use-catalog or use-schema is the trap. Two: "which columns' values" means column mask; "which rows" means row filter; and "across many tables," or "centralised," means A-B-A-C. Three: "who accessed, when, or lineage" means the system-dot-access schema.

And that completes the exam's seven sections. Let me leave you with the recurring instinct that wins across this whole certification: when two answers compete, pick the more managed, declarative, base-table-enforced, Databricks-recommended one. Here, that means masks, filters, and A-B-A-C over dynamic views, and groups over individual users. Carry that instinct into the exam, match each scenario to the purpose-built feature, and you'll be in very good shape. Good luck.
